                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6 text-left text-md-right d-print-none">
                            <ul class="social-links list-unsyled list-inline mt-4 mt-md-0">
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2004/11/suffering-education" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-facebook"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2004/11/suffering-education&amp;text=Suffering an education" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=Suffering%20an%20education%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2004%2F11%2Fsuffering-education" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>Moving minds, changing perception, provoking thought&mdash;these mantras have been my credo as an aspiring writer. Yet the last two weeks have demonstrated that a string of alphanumeric characters invokes a unique meaning for each reader, well beyond my control. Evidence and logic are matters of the mind; they mean little to the heart. I resort, instead, to my experience, which is all I have ever known.</p>
<p>Ciudad del Este, PARAGUAY: A semester of transnational study in South America leads me to an indigenous village, remote from Paraguay&rsquo;s capital and economic center in Asunci&oacute;n. Of course, the locals are still trying to make a buck off na&iuml;ve estadounidenses, so as I open my wallet to pay for a sample of home-brewed Paraguayan moonshine, I catch a glimpse of the different bills I&rsquo;ve collected on my recent excursions: Argentinean and Uruguayan pesos, Brazilian reales and Paraguayan guaranies. The inks span the gamut of colors&mdash;purples, blues, oranges, reds&mdash;and some money even boasts artwork and battle scenes. In this moment I can&rsquo;t help but think to myself, for the first time, how it is the U.S. dollar that looks weird, and not this foreign currency I once considered fit for Monopoly. Maybe my country isn&rsquo;t the normal one, after all.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>Physics Building, SCIENCE DRIVE: I&rsquo;m having trouble wrapping my head around the fundamentals of quantum mechanics. The three-dimensional space in which we live makes sense&mdash;in fact, I&rsquo;m pretty good at doodling those cool little cubes we all sketch in boredom, out of two overlapping squares and four straight lines. I can visualize arrows rotating and morphing in this familiar world. But quantum mechanics requires something radically different&mdash;an abstract generalization of these arrows to infinite dimensions, and my mind can&rsquo;t keep up with what mathematicians insist is correct. I become lost, unable to comprehend what I cannot see. Empathizing with this confusion, my professor urges me to believe in infiniteness&mdash;what he knows to be true&mdash;and trust the underlying mathematical structure of the universe. Only then, he promises, will I begin to understand its secrets.</p>
<p>A similar situation has emerged in my column. Two weeks ago, I had an idea. I wrote about the idea, in order to spark conversation. Some people disagreed with my words, and others agreed. Some thought my words should have been presented differently, and others thought they shouldn&rsquo;t have been presented at all. Like in any conflict, my emotions have progressed through stages.</p>
<p>DEFENSIVENESS</p>
<p>I feel misunderstood by critics:</p>
<p>&ldquo;You sicken me to the core, but I am not angry with your anti-Semitic trash. People like me will do anything to prevent people like you from getting a job anywhere, you Nazi scum.&rdquo;</p>
<p>I don&rsquo;t understand why we can&rsquo;t discuss these issues, or how we could. I see some great injustice in our incapacity to consider ideas we find abhorrent.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>REMORSE</p>
<p>Not light from the shrine at Weimar beyond the hill</p>
<p>Nor light from heaven appeared. But he did refuse.</p>
<p>A L&uuml;ger settled back deeply in its glove.</p>
                            
    
<div class="mc-signup my-4 p-4 text-center " id="mc-container" data-mc="c4087a59c7">
